adrenal haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute adrenal tuberculosis","Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome","Primary adrenal insufficiency","Bilateral adrenal metastases","Secondary adrenal insufficiency"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has \u003Cstrong\u003EWaterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by acute adrenal failure due to bilateral adrenal haemorrhage in the setting of severe meningococcal septicaemia. The classic presentation includes shock, purpura, and adrenal failure. The condition is rapidly progressive and often fatal without prompt treatment with intravenous antibiotics and corticosteroids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute adrenal tuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a more gradual onset of adrenal insufficiency without haemorrhage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary adrenal insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E (Addison disease) develops over months to years\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral adrenal metastases\u003C/strong\u003E usually occur in the setting of known malignancy and cause gradual onset of symptoms\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecondary adrenal insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is due to pituitary dysfunction rather than direct adrenal damage\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly recognition is crucial as the mortality rate is high without immediate intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome is acute adrenal failure due to bilateral adrenal haemorrhage, typically caused by meningococcal septicaemia","The classic triad includes shock, purpura, and adrenal failure","Immediate treatment with antibiotics and steroids is essential for survival"],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA","Lotfi CFP, Kremer JL, Dos Santos Passaia B, Cavalcante IP. The human adrenal cortex: growth control and disorders. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2018 Sep 6;73(suppl 1):e473s. doi: 10.6061/clinics/2018/e473s. PMID: 30208164; PMCID: PMC6113920"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56501"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15652"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56501"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T19:03:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T19:04:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8343"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71030"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21